commentBody:
@josh locy

Maybe the constructor was GOOFingOFF too much to think of a new clue and answer... Har!

I think it was meant to be a bit meta. Pezhead above wrote that it only takes eight RIFFLESHUFFLES to bring the deck back to it's original configuration. I know there aren't eight shuffles in the puzzle, but may still be a nod to that.

@Steve L

Is this substantially in service of the theme? I guess it’s kind of cool that GOOFOFFS “shuffled” is GOOFOFFS, but it doesn’t exactly make or break the theme.

I think the last puzzle that repeated answers was (spoiler alert) one this year that “recycled” the answer CAN multiple times. Repeated answers rarely happen, but usually when they do they make a lot more sense than here.

@josh locy

Yeah, very odd. The other “decks” had different clues, different answers. This one: same clue, same answer. It seems like a mistake, but someone would have caught that.

There’s something going on here that I just don’t understand.

@josh locy,

I thought it was just to show that even after the shuffle, the word comes out the same. Pretty clever to find a word like that. 

So using the same clue is icing on the cake.

@HeathieJ,
I believe that was indeed intentional. As was the later DOGIT
Minimal effort, and cluing GOOFOFF the same way twice  are Easter eggs within the puzzle construction. Clever.

@Mike

I gotta be straight with you Mike,
you should have flushed that joke.

@Chris

Only if “super obscure” simply means “I never heard of it.”  OSSO BUCO is on the menu in practically every full-service Italian restaurant. I don’t even eat it, but I’ve seen it on menus with regularity. 

And you live in Boston, not, say, Warsaw.

@Steve L

Oddly, Steve, I seem to know it mainly from crosswords. I eat in a ton of Italian restaurants—maybe not the fanciest ones—and rarely see it on the menu, or maybe it’s there and I just don’t pay attention to it because I wouldn’t recognize it if you hit me on the head with it. Don’t get me wrong it’s common enough that I absolutely agree it’s fair game
In a crossword, and if it’s obscure to the OP they better learn it because they will certainly see it here again and again. But do understand there’s a ton of worldly, cultured people who honestly haven’t come across it meaningfully in real life.

@SP
